04524nam a22005055i 9781447366683DE-B159720230328044521.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230328t20062006xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a9781447366683  a(DE-B1597)646990  a(OCoLC)1340094852  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB-BST 7aSOC0040002bisacsh1 aClancy, Anna, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aResearching Criminal Justice. Getting out and staying out :bResults of the prisoner Resettlement Pathfinders /cAnna Clancy, Kirsty Hudson, Mike Maguire, Richard Peake, Peter Raynor, Maurice Vanstone, Jocelyn Kynch. 1aBristol : bPolicy Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (0 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aResearching Criminal Justice00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of tables and figures -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction: prisoner resettlement and the Pathfinders -- tThe ‘FOR – A Change’ programme and its delivery -- tPre-release interventions: staff and offender perspectives -- tPost-release contact and services -- tImpact and outcome measures -- tOrganisational and implementation issues -- tConclusions -- tReferences -- tSupplementary tables and figures -- tHeadings of the 13 sessions in the ‘FOR – A Change’ programme -- tConversion of OGRS2 24-month predicted reconviction rates into 12-month predictions -- tPrediction of reconvictions: OGRS2, OASys and CRIME-PICS II0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aShort-term prisoners have exceptionally high reconviction rates, fuelled by major social problems. Growing recognition of this, and of deficiencies in prison-probation coordination, has accelerated 'resettlement' of ex-prisoners up the penal agenda.  The 'Resettlement Pathfinders' tested several new partnership-based approaches. This report evaluates three probation-led projects which combined practical assistance with interventions to improve motivation and capacity to change. Their key feature was the delivery of a cognitive-motivational programme ('FOR - A Change') specially designed for short-termers. The study found this produced significant changes in attitude, as well as greater 'continuity' (voluntary post-release contact between offenders and project staff) than previous approaches. It also found evidence of association between continuity and reduced reconviction. Overall, the findings support resettlement strategies based on fostering and nurturing offenders' motivation to change, facilitating access to services, and 'through the gate' contact with staff or volunteers with whom a relationship has already been built. The research offers findings and insights of practical value to probation and prison officers, as well as staff of other agencies that work with prisoners and ex-prisoners. The report should also be read by penal policy-makers, criminology/criminal justice academics and students, and those engaged in staff training.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh1 aHudson, Kirsty, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKynch, Jocelyn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMaguire, Mike, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aRaynor, Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aVanstone, Maurice, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-1995z978311119621340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781447366683423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781447366683/original  a978-3-11-119621-3  Bristol University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-1995c1995d2013  aG